{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645176"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18089"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18089"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.2,0.15,0.25,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10803"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96557"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25167"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMucins are essential glycoproteins found throughout the human body that help protect epithelial surfaces.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key structural characteristic of mucin proteins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extensive O-linked glycosylation on serine and threonine residues","N-linked glycosylation on asparagine residues","Phosphorylation of tyrosine residues","High content of hydrophobic amino acids","Multiple disulfide bonds between cysteine residues"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe defining characteristic of mucins is \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensive O-linked glycosylation on serine and threonine residues\u003C/strong\u003E. These O-linked oligosaccharide chains make up 50-80% of the molecular mass and give mucins their gel-forming and protective properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh content of hydrophobic amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of mucins as they are actually hydrophilic due to their extensive glycosylation. \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple disulfide bonds between cysteine residues\u003C/strong\u003E may be present in some mucins but this is not their key defining feature. \u003Cstrong\u003EN-linked glycosylation on asparagine residues\u003C/strong\u003E may occur in mucins but O-linked glycosylation is far more extensive and characteristic. \u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphorylation of tyrosine residues\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with cell signalling proteins rather than mucins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe extensive O-linked glycosylation creates a bottle brush-like structure that allows mucins to trap water and form protective barriers on epithelial surfaces.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mucins are high molecular weight glycoproteins that form protective barriers on mucosal surfaces.","Secreted mucins form gel-like barriers while membrane-bound mucins contribute to cell signalling.","O-linked glycosylation is the key post-translational modification that gives mucins their protective properties."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019.","Boron WF, Boulpaep EL. Medical Physiology. 3rd ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships"